TY  - JOUR
T1  - Dynamic Pricing for Network Service: Equilibrium and Stability
AU  - Masuda, Yasushi
AU  - Whang, Seungjin
Y1  - 1999/06/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.45.6.857
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.45.6.857
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 857
EP  - 869
VL  - 45
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Consider a data communication network owned and operated by a single organization. The network has an infinite number of small users and is managed by a system manager (SM) whose objective is to maximize the net value of the system as a whole. The objective of this paper is to study pricing mechanisms that induce the optimal arrival rates when the SM has no full knowledge of the demand in advance. We investigate the system behavior under three alternative dynamic pricing rules and users' expectations models, and characterize the equilibrium and its stability conditions.
AB  - Consider a data communication network owned and operated by a single organization. The network has an infinite number of small users and is managed by a system manager (SM) whose objective is to maximize the net value of the system as a whole. The objective of this paper is to study pricing mechanisms that induce the optimal arrival rates when the SM has no full knowledge of the demand in advance. We investigate the system behavior under three alternative dynamic pricing rules and users' expectations models, and characterize the equilibrium and its stability conditions.
